      "bundle": {
        "postUri": "x://1085245460825149443/status/2042159952765055188",
        "assetKey": "embed:0:https://pbs.twimg.com/media/HFc1dP2XMAA5Aco.jpg",
        "postText": [
          "While gas prices remain volatile a month into the Iran war, they have consistently stayed higher than pre-crisis levels throughout the last month.  \n\nIn Europe, gas is used not only for heating homes but also to generate electricity, especially during hours when demand cannot be met by renewables.  \n\nWith peak prices now having to take a new gas price regime into account, but midday prices still being set by renewables, the daily spread between highest-priced and lowest-priced hours widens.  \n\nFor batteries, that is good news: charging at low prices in the middle of the day, but earning higher peak prices when discharging into the evening peak set by gas (no European country so far has enough battery capacity to displace gas completely during peak hours).  \n\nOf course, spreads typically widen from February to March in line with seasonal expectations - more solar irradiation, more hours where renewables can set the price at or near zero."
        ],
        "chartTitle": "Battery spreads rose sharply in March driven by higher gas prices",
        "xAxis": {
